# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: swarm-robotics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In computer science and operations research, the **ant colony optimization** algorithm (**ACO**) is a probabilistic technique for solving computational problems that can be reduced to finding good paths through graphs.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Artificial ants represent multi-agent methods inspired by the behavior of real ants.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The pheromone-based communication of biological ants is often the predominant paradigm used.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Combinations of artificial ants and local search algorithms have become a preferred method for numerous optimization tasks involving some sort of graph, e.g., vehicle routing and internet routing.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] As an example, ant colony optimization is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Artificial 'ants' (e.g. simulation agents) locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Real ants lay down pheromones to direct each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The simulated 'ants' similarly, record their positions and the quality of their solutions so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate better solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] One variation on this approach is the bees algorithm, which is more analogous to the foraging patterns of the honey bee, another social insect.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm is a member of the ant colony algorithms family, in swarm intelligence methods, and it constitutes some metaheuristic optimizations.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Initially proposed by Marco Dorigo in 1992 in his PhD thesis, the first algorithm was aiming to search for an optimal path in a graph, based on the behavior of ants seeking a path between their colony and a source of food.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The original idea has since diversified to solve a wider class of numerical problems, and as a result, several problems have emerged, drawing on various aspects of the behavior of ants.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] From a broader perspective, ACO performs a model-based search and shares some similarities with estimation of distribution algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the natural world, ants of some species (initially) wander randomly, and upon finding food return to their colony while laying down pheromone trails.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] If other ants find such a path, they are likely to stop travelling at random and instead follow the trail, returning and reinforcing it if they eventually find food (see Ant communication).
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Over time, however, the pheromone trail starts to evaporate, thus reducing its attractive strength.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The more time it takes for an ant to travel down the path and back again, the more time the pheromones have to evaporate.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A short path, by comparison, is marched over more frequently, and thus the pheromone density becomes higher on shorter paths than longer ones.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone evaporation also has the advantage of avoiding the convergence to a locally optimal solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] If there were no evaporation at all, the paths chosen by the first ants would tend to be excessively attractive to the following ones.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In that case, the exploration of the solution space would be constrained.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The influence of pheromone evaporation in real ant systems is unclear, but it is very important in artificial systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The overall result is that when one ant finds a good (i.e., short) path from the colony to a food source, other ants are more likely to follow that path, and positive feedback eventually leads to many ants following a single path.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The idea of the ant colony algorithm is to mimic this behavior with "simulated ants" walking around the graph representing the problem to be solved.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] New concepts are required since "intelligence" is no longer centralized but can be found throughout all minuscule objects.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Anthropocentric concepts have been known to lead to the production of IT systems in which data processing, control units and calculating power are centralized.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] These centralized units have continually increased their performance and can be compared to the human brain.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The model of the brain has become the ultimate vision of computers.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Ambient networks of intelligent objects and, sooner or later, a new generation of information systems that are even more diffused and based on nanotechnology, will profoundly change this concept.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Small devices that can be compared to insects do not possess a high intelligence on their own.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Indeed, their intelligence can be classed as fairly limited.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is, for example, impossible to integrate a high performance calculator with the power to solve any kind of mathematical problem into a biochip that is implanted into the human body or integrated in an intelligent tag designed to trace commercial articles.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, once those objects are interconnected they develop a form of intelligence that can be compared to a colony of ants or bees.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the case of certain problems, this type of intelligence can be superior to the reasoning of a centralized system similar to the brain.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Nature offers several examples of how minuscule organisms, if they all follow the same basic rule, can create a form of collective intelligence on the macroscopic level.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Colonies of social insects perfectly illustrate this model which greatly differs from human societies.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This model is based on the cooperation of independent units with simple and unpredictable behavior.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They move through their surrounding area to carry out certain tasks and only possess a very limited amount of information to do so.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A colony of ants, for example, represents numerous qualities that can also be applied to a network of ambient objects.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Colonies of ants have a very high capacity to adapt themselves to changes in the environment, as well as great strength in dealing with situations where one individual fails to carry out a given task.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This kind of flexibility would also be very useful for mobile networks of objects which are perpetually developing.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Parcels of information that move from a computer to a digital object behave in the same way as ants would do.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They move through the network and pass from one node to the next with the objective of arriving at their final destination as quickly as possible.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone-based communication is one of the most effective ways of communication which is widely observed in nature.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone is used by social insects such as bees, ants and termites; both for inter-agent and agent-swarm communications.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Due to its feasibility, artificial pheromones have been adopted in multi-robot and swarm robotic systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Pheromone-based communication was implemented by different means such as chemical or physical (RFID tags, light, sound) ways.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, those implementations were not able to replicate all the aspects of pheromones as seen in nature.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Using projected light was presented in a 2007 IEEE paper by Garnier, Simon, et al. as an experimental setup to study pheromone-based communication with micro autonomous robots.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Another study presented a system in which pheromones were implemented via a horizontal LCD screen on which the robots moved, with the robots having downward facing light sensors to register the patterns beneath them.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the ant colony optimization algorithms, an artificial ant is a simple computational agent that searches for good solutions to a given optimization problem.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To apply an ant colony algorithm, the optimization problem needs to be converted into the problem of finding the shortest path on a weighted graph.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the first step of each iteration, each ant stochastically constructs a solution, i.e. the order in which the edges in the graph should be followed.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In the second step, the paths found by the different ants are compared.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The last step consists of updating the pheromone levels on each edge.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Each ant needs to construct a solution to move through the graph.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To select the next edge in its tour, an ant will consider the length of each edge available from its current position, as well as the corresponding pheromone level.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] At each step of the algorithm, each ant moves from a state x to state y , corresponding to a more complete intermediate solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Thus, each ant k computes a set $A_{k}(x)$ of feasible expansions to its current state in each iteration, and moves to one of these in probability.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The *trail level* represents a posteriori indication of the desirability of that move.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Trails are usually updated when all ants have completed their solution, increasing or decreasing the level of trails corresponding to moves that were part of "good" or "bad" solutions, respectively.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] where $L_{k}$ is the cost of the k th ant's tour (typically length) and Q is a constant.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Here are some of the most popular variations of ACO algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The ant system is the first ACO algorithm.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm corresponds to the one presented above.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] At the end of each iteration, only the best ant is allowed to update the trails by applying a modified global pheromone updating rule.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In this algorithm, the global best solution deposits pheromone on its trail after every iteration (even if this trail has not been revisited), along with all the other ants.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The elitist strategy has as its objective directing the search of all ants to construct a solution to contain links of the current best route.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This algorithm controls the maximum and minimum pheromone amounts on each trail.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Only the global best tour or the iteration best tour are allowed to add pheromone to its trail.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To avoid stagnation of the search algorithm, the range of possible pheromone amounts on each trail is limited to an interval [τmax,τmin].
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] All edges are initialized to τmax to force a higher exploration of solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The trails are reinitialized to τmax when nearing stagnation.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] All solutions are ranked according to their length.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Only a fixed number of the best ants in this iteration are allowed to update their trials.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The amount of pheromone deposited is weighted for each solution, such that solutions with shorter paths deposit more pheromone than the solutions with longer paths.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An ant colony system (ACS) with communication strategies is developed.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The artificial ants are partitioned into several groups.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Seven communication methods for updating the pheromone level between groups in ACS are proposed and work on the traveling salesman problem.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The pheromone deposit mechanism of COAC is to enable ants to search for solutions collaboratively and effectively.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] By using an orthogonal design method, ants in the feasible domain can explore their chosen regions rapidly and efficiently, with enhanced global search capability and accuracy.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The orthogonal design method and the adaptive radius adjustment method can also be extended to other optimization algorithms for delivering wider advantages in solving practical problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is a recursive form of ant system which divides the whole search domain into several sub-domains and solves the objective on these subdomains.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The results from all the subdomains are compared and the best few of them are promoted for the next level.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The subdomains corresponding to the selected results are further subdivided and the process is repeated until an output of desired precision is obtained.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This method has been tested on ill-posed geophysical inversion problems and works well.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] For some versions of the algorithm, it is possible to prove that it is convergent (i.e., it is able to find the global optimum in finite time).
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The first evidence of convergence for an ant colony algorithm was made in 2000, the graph-based ant system algorithm, and later on for the ACS and MMAS algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Like most metaheuristics, it is very difficult to estimate the theoretical speed of convergence.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In 2004, Zlochin and his colleagues showed that ACO-type algorithms are closely related to stochastic gradient descent, Cross-entropy method and estimation of distribution algorithm.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They proposed an umbrella term "Model-based search" to describe this class of metaheuristics.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It has also been used to produce near-optimal solutions to the travelling salesman problem.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They have an advantage over simulated annealing and genetic algorithm approaches of similar problems when the graph may change dynamically; the ant colony algorithm can be run continuously and adapt to changes in real time.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This is of interest in network routing and urban transportation systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The first ACO algorithm was called the ant system and it was aimed to solve the travelling salesman problem, in which the goal is to find the shortest round-trip to link a series of cities.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The general algorithm is relatively simple and based on a set of ants, each making one of the possible round-trips along the cities.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] After each iteration, trails of pheromones evaporate.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To optimize the form of antennas, ant colony algorithms can be used.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The ACO algorithm is used in image processing for image edge detection and edge linking.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The graph here is the 2-D image and the ants traverse from one pixel depositing pheromone.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The movement of ants from one pixel to another is directed by the local variation of the image's intensity values.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This movement causes the highest density of the pheromone to be deposited at the edges.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] There are various methods to determine the heuristic matrix.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] For the below example the heuristic matrix was calculated based on the local statistics: the local statistics at the pixel position $(i,j)$ .
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The parameter $\lambda$ in each of above functions adjusts the functions' respective shapes.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Image edge detected using ACO: The images below are generated using different functions given by the equation (1) to (4).
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] With an ACO algorithm, the shortest path in a graph, between two points A and B, is built from a combination of several paths.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is not easy to give a precise definition of what algorithm is or is not an ant colony, because the definition may vary according to the authors and uses.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Broadly speaking, ant colony algorithms are regarded as populated metaheuristics with each solution represented by an ant moving in the search space.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Ants mark the best solutions and take account of previous markings to optimize their search.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] They can be seen as probabilistic multi-agent algorithms using a probability distribution to make the transition between each iteration.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In their versions for combinatorial problems, they use an iterative construction of solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] According to some authors, the thing which distinguishes ACO algorithms from other relatives (such as algorithms to estimate the distribution or particle swarm optimization) is precisely their constructive aspect.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In combinatorial problems, it is possible that the best solution eventually be found, even though no ant would prove effective.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Thus, in the example of the travelling salesman problem, it is not necessary that an ant actually travels the shortest route: the shortest route can be built from the strongest segments of the best solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] However, this definition can be problematic in the case of problems in real variables, where no structure of 'neighbours' exists.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The collective behaviour of social insects remains a source of inspiration for researchers.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The wide variety of algorithms (for optimization or not) seeking self-organization in biological systems has led to the concept of "swarm intelligence", which is a very general framework in which ant colony algorithms fit.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] There is in practice a large number of algorithms claiming to be "ant colonies", without always sharing the general framework of optimization by canonical ant colonies.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] In practice, the use of an exchange of information between ants via the environment (a principle called "stigmergy") is deemed enough for an algorithm to belong to the class of ant colony algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] This principle has led some authors to create the term "value" to organize methods and behavior based on search of food, sorting larvae, division of labour and cooperative transportation.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] These maintain a pool of solutions rather than just one.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The process of finding superior solutions mimics that of evolution, with solutions being combined or mutated to alter the pool of solutions, with solutions of inferior quality being discarded.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] that substitutes traditional reproduction operators by model-guided operators.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A related global optimization technique which traverses the search space by generating neighboring solutions of the current solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An inferior neighbor is accepted probabilistically based on the difference in quality and a temperature parameter.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] The temperature parameter is modified as the algorithm progresses to alter the nature of the search.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Focuses on combining machine learning with optimization, by adding an internal feedback loop to self-tune the free parameters of an algorithm to the characteristics of the problem, of the instance, and of the local situation around the current solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Similar to simulated annealing in that both traverse the solution space by testing mutations of an individual solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] While simulated annealing generates only one mutated solution, tabu search generates many mutated solutions and moves to the solution with the lowest fitness of those generated.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] To prevent cycling and encourage greater movement through the solution space, a tabu list is maintained of partial or complete solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] It is forbidden to move to a solution that contains elements of the tabu list, which is updated as the solution traverses the solution space.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] A method that make use of clustering approach, extending the ACO.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] An agent-based probabilistic global search and optimization technique best suited to problems where the objective function can be decomposed into multiple independent partial-functions.
[src:swarm-robotics/ant-colony-optimization-algorithms] Chronology of ant colony optimization algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] Like most artificial life simulations, Boids is an example of emergent behavior; that is, the complexity of Boids arises from the interaction of individual agents (the boids, in this case) adhering to a set of simple rules.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] More complex rules can be added, such as obstacle avoidance and goal seeking.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] The basic model has been extended in several different ways since Reynolds proposed it.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] For instance, Delgado-Mata et al. extended the basic model to incorporate the effects of fear.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] Olfaction was used to transmit emotion between animals, through pheromones modelled as particles in a free expansion gas.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] Hartman and Benes introduced a complementary force to the alignment that they call the change of leadership.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] This steer defines the chance of the boid to become a leader and try to escape.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] The movement of Boids can be characterized as either chaotic (splitting groups and wild behaviour) or orderly.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] Unexpected behaviours, such as splitting flocks and reuniting after avoiding obstacles, can be considered emergent.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] The boids framework is often used in computer graphics, providing realistic-looking representations of flocks of birds and other creatures, such as schools of fish or herds of animals.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] It was for instance used in the 1998 video game *Half-Life* for the flying bird-like creatures seen at the end of the game on Xen, named "boid" in the game files.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] The Boids model can be used for direct control and stabilization of teams of simple unmanned ground vehicles (UGV) or micro aerial vehicles (MAV) in swarm robotics.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] For stabilization of heterogeneous UAV-UGV teams, the model was adapted for using onboard relative localization by Saska et al.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] At the time of proposal, Reynolds' approach represented a giant step forward compared to the traditional techniques used in computer animation for motion pictures.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] The first animation created with the model was *Stanley and Stella in: Breaking the Ice* (1987), followed by a feature film debut in Tim Burton's film *Batman Returns* (1992) with computer-generated bat swarms and armies of penguins marching through the streets of Gotham City.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] The boids model has been used for other interesting applications.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] It has been applied to automatically program Internet multi-channel radio stations.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] It has also been used for visualizing information and for optimization tasks.
[src:swarm-robotics/boids] Biologist Richard Dawkins references the Boids model in his 2009 book *The Greatest Show on Earth: The Evidence for Evolution*.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] DAI is closely related to and a predecessor of the field of multi-agent systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] They are distinguished generally by multi-agent systems being open, where the entities might arise from different interests and have individual goals, and distributed artificial-intelligence systems, where the entities have common goals.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] There are numerous applications and tools.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] Distributed Artificial Intelligence (DAI) is an approach to solving complex learning, planning, and decision-making problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] It is embarrassingly parallel, thus able to exploit large scale computation and spatial distribution of computing resources.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] These properties allow it to solve problems that require the processing of very large data sets.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] DAI systems consist of autonomous learning processing nodes (agents), that are distributed, often at a very large scale.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] DAI nodes can act independently, and partial solutions are integrated by communication between nodes, often asynchronously.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] By virtue of their scale, DAI systems are robust and elastic, and by necessity, loosely coupled.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] Furthermore, DAI systems are built to be adaptive to changes in the problem definition or underlying data sets due to the scale and difficulty in redeployment.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] DAI systems do not require all the relevant data to be aggregated in a single location, in contrast to monolithic or centralized Artificial Intelligence systems, which have tightly coupled and geographically close processing nodes.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] Therefore, DAI systems often operate on sub-samples or hashed impressions of very large datasets.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] In addition, the source dataset may change or be updated during the course of the execution of a DAI system.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] In 1975 distributed artificial intelligence emerged as a subfield of artificial intelligence that dealt with interactions of intelligent agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] Distributed artificial intelligence systems were conceived as a group of intelligent entities, called agents, that interacted by cooperation, by coexistence, or by competition.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] DAI is categorized into multi-agent systems and distributed problem solving.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] In multi-agent systems the main focus is how agents coordinate their knowledge and activities.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] For distributed problem solving the major focus is how the problem is decomposed and the solutions are synthesized.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] The objectives of Distributed Artificial Intelligence are to solve the reasoning, planning, learning and perception problems of artificial intelligence, especially if they require large data, by distributing the problem to autonomous processing nodes (agents).
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] There are many reasons for wanting to distribute intelligence or cope with multi-agent systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] DAI can apply a bottom-up approach to AI, similar to the subsumption architecture as well as the traditional top-down approach of AI.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] In addition, DAI can also be a vehicle for emergence.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] How to synthesise the results among 'intelligent agents' group by formulation, description, decomposition and allocation.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] Notion of Agents: Agents can be described as distinct entities with standard boundaries and interfaces designed for problem solving.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] Notion of Multi-Agents: Multi-Agent system is defined as a network of agents which are loosely coupled working as a single entity like society for problem solving that an individual agent cannot solve.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] The key concept used in DPS and MABS is the abstraction called software agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] An agent is a virtual (or physical) autonomous entity that has an understanding of its environment and acts upon it.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] An agent is usually able to communicate with other agents in the same system to achieve a common goal, that one agent alone could not achieve.
[src:swarm-robotics/distributed-artificial-intelligence] This communication system uses an agent communication language.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] A **multi-agent system** (**MAS**) or "self-organized system" is a computational system composed of multiple interacting intelligent agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Multi-agent systems can solve problems that are difficult or impossible for an individual agent or a monolithic system to solve.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Intelligence may include methodic, functional, procedural approaches, algorithmic search or reinforcement learning.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] With advancements in large language models (LLMs), LLM-based multi-agent systems have emerged as a new area of research, enabling more sophisticated interactions and coordination among agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Despite considerable overlap, a multi-agent system is not always the same as an agent-based model (ABM).
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] The goal of an ABM is to search for explanatory insight into the collective behavior of agents (which do not necessarily need to be "intelligent") obeying simple rules, typically in natural systems, rather than in solving specific practical or engineering problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] The terminology of ABM tends to be used more often in the science, and MAS in engineering and technology.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Applications where multi-agent systems research may deliver an appropriate approach include online trading, disaster response, target surveillance and social structure modelling.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Multi-agent systems consist of agents and their environment.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Typically, research on multi-agent systems refers to software agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] However, the agents in a multi-agent system could equally well be robots, humans, or human teams, and may consist of combined human-agent teams.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Agents can be divided into types spanning simple to complex.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Agent actions are typically mediated via an appropriate middleware.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] This middleware offers a first-class design abstraction for multi-agent systems, providing means to govern resource access and agent coordination.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Multi-agent systems can manifest self-organisation as well as self-direction and other control paradigms and related complex behaviors even when the individual strategies of all their agents are simple.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] When agents can share knowledge using any agreed language, within the constraints of the system's communication protocol, the approach may lead to a common improvement.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Example languages are Knowledge Query Manipulation Language (KQML) or Agent Communication Language (ACL).
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Decision protocols in multi-agent systems refer to the structured rules and procedures that agents follow to reach collective decisions or agreements.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Such protocols specify how agents share information, negotiate, and resolve conflicts, ensuring coordinated behavior and effective joint actions.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Decision protocols can range from voting mechanisms to consensus-building algorithms, and they significantly influence the efficiency and reliability of multi-agent interactions.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Many MAS are implemented in computer simulations, stepping the system through discrete "time steps".
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] The MAS components communicate typically using a weighted request matrix, e.g.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] also considering other components, evolving "contracts" and the restriction sets of the component algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Another paradigm commonly used with MAS is the "pheromone", where components leave information for other nearby components.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] These pheromones may evaporate/concentrate with time, that is their values may decrease (or increase).
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] MAS tend to find the best solution for their problems without intervention.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] There is high similarity here to physical phenomena, such as energy minimizing, where physical objects tend to reach the lowest energy possible within the physically constrained world.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] For example: many of the cars entering a metropolis in the morning will be available for leaving that same metropolis in the evening.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] The systems also tend to prevent propagation of faults, self-recover and be fault tolerant, mainly due to the redundancy of components.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] A MAS involves more than just the design of an intelligent system.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] It also provides insights and understanding about interactions among humans, as they organize themselves into various groups, committees, societies, and economies in order to improve their lives.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] For example, economists have been studying multiple agents for more than two hundred years, ever since Adam Smith in the eighteenth century, with the goal of being able to understand and predict economies.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Economics provides ways to characterize masses of agents. and these are useful for DAI.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] But in return, DAI provides a means to construct artificial economies that can test economists’ theories before, rather than after, they are applied.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Frameworks have emerged that implement common standards (such as the FIPA and OMG MASIF standards).
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] JADE, save time and aid in the standardization of MAS development.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Currently though, no standard is actively maintained from FIPA or OMG.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Efforts for further development of software agents in industrial context are carried out in IEEE IES technical committee on Industrial Agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] With advancements in large language models (LLMs) such as ChatGPT, LLM-based multi-agent frameworks, such as CAMEL, have emerged as a new paradigm for developing multi-agent applications.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Recent work has shown that such debate-oriented systems vary in their orchestration (e.g., discussion paradigms).
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] The MALLM framework is used to systematically evaluate possible configurations of frameworks.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] MAS have not only been applied in academic research, but also in industry.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] MAS are applied in the real world to graphical applications such as computer games.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] It is widely advocated for use in networking and mobile technologies, to achieve automatic and dynamic load balancing, high scalability and self-healing networks.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] They are being used for coordinated defence systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Other applications include transportation, logistics, graphics, manufacturing, power system, smartgrids, and the GIS.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Also, Multi-agent Systems Artificial Intelligence (MAAI) are used for simulating societies, the purpose thereof being helpful in the fields of climate, energy, epidemiology, conflict management, child abuse, ....
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Some organisations working on using multi-agent system models include Center for Modelling Social Systems, Centre for Research in Social Simulation, Centre for Policy Modelling, Society for Modelling and Simulation International.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Vehicular traffic with controlled autonomous vehicles can be modelling as a multi-agent system involving crowd dynamics.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Hallerbach et al. discussed the application of agent-based approaches for the development and validation of automated driving systems via a digital twin of the vehicle-under-test and microscopic traffic simulation based on independent agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] Waymo has created a multi-agent simulation environment Carcraft to test algorithms for self-driving cars.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] It simulates traffic interactions between human drivers, pedestrians and automated vehicles.
[src:swarm-robotics/multi-agent-system] People's behavior is imitated by artificial agents based on data of real human behavior.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] In computational science, **particle swarm optimization** (**PSO**) is a computational method that optimizes a problem by iteratively trying to improve a population of candidate solutions with regard to a given measure of quality.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] It solves a problem through interactions among a population of candidate solutions, dubbed particles, moving the particles around in the search-space according to simple mathematical formulae that adjust each particle's position and velocity.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Each particle's movement is influenced by its own best known position so far, and by the best known position in its topological neighborhood (which may include the entire population if so specified); vectors are updated as better positions are found.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This is expected to move the swarm toward good solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] PSO is originally attributed to Kennedy and Eberhart and was first intended for simulating social behaviour, as a stylized representation of the movement of organisms in a bird flock or fish school, or the evolution of attitudes in a human population.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Simulation of principles of social behavior was observed to be capable of solving hard mathematical problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The book by Kennedy and Eberhart describes many philosophical aspects of PSO and swarm intelligence.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] An extensive survey of PSO applications is made by Poli.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] In 2017, a comprehensive review on theoretical and experimental works on PSO was published by Bonyadi and Michalewicz.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] PSO is a metaheuristic as it makes few or no assumptions about the problem being optimized and can search very large spaces of candidate solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Also, PSO does not use the gradient of the problem being optimized, which means PSO does not require that the optimization problem be differentiable as is required by classic optimization methods such as gradient descent and quasi-newton methods.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] However, metaheuristics such as PSO do not guarantee an optimal solution is ever found.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] A basic variant of the PSO algorithm is initialized with a connected population (called a swarm) of candidate solutions (called particles).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] A candidate solution is a vector of numeric values which can be considered as coordinates of a point in a search space; as an iteratively moving point it can be conceptualized as a particle.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The particles move around in the search-space according to a few simple formulae.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Each particle has some neighbors it is connected to, where the neighborhood may be a few or all other population members.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The next position of a particle is stochastically determined by its own best-so-far position in the search space as well as the particle's best neighbor's best-so-far position.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] When an improved position is discovered - one that produces a better result in the objective function - the best-so-far position of the particle is updated.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The process is repeated and by doing so it is expected, but not guaranteed, that a satisfactory solution will eventually be discovered.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Formally, let *f*: ℝ*n* → ℝ be the cost function which must be minimized.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The function takes a candidate solution as an argument in the form of a vector of real numbers and produces a real number as output which indicates the objective function value of the given candidate solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The goal is to find a solution **a** for which *f*(**a**) ≤ *f*(**b**) for all **b** in the search-space, which would mean **a** is the global minimum.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Let *S* be the number of particles in the swarm, each having a position **x**i ∈ ℝ*n* in the search-space and a velocity **v**i ∈ ℝ*n*.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Let **p**i be the best known position of particle *i* and let **g** be the best known position of the particle's neighborhood.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The values **blo** and **bup** represent the lower and upper boundaries of the search-space respectively.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The parameters φp and φg are often called cognitive coefficient and social coefficient.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The termination criterion can be the number of iterations performed, or a solution where the adequate objective function value is found.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The parameters w, φp, and φg are selected by the practitioner and control the behaviour and efficacy of the PSO method (below).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The choice of PSO parameters can have a large impact on optimization performance.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Selecting PSO parameters that yield good performance has therefore been the subject of much research.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] To prevent divergence ("explosion") the inertia weight must be smaller than 1.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The two other parameters can be then derived thanks to the constriction approach, or freely selected, but the analyses suggest convergence domains to constrain them.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The PSO parameters can also be tuned by using another overlaying optimizer, a concept known as meta-optimization, or even fine-tuned during the optimization, e.g., by means of fuzzy logic.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Parameters have also been tuned for various optimization scenarios.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The topology of the swarm defines the subset of particles with which each particle can exchange information.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The basic version of the algorithm uses the global topology as the swarm communication structure.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This topology allows all particles to communicate with all the other particles, thus the whole swarm share the same best position **g** from a single particle.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] However, this approach might lead the swarm to be trapped into a local minimum, thus different topologies have been used to control the flow of information among particles.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] For instance, in local topologies, particles only share information with a subset of particles.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This subset can be a geometrical one – for example "the *m* nearest particles" – or, more often, a social one, i.e. a set of particles that is not depending on any distance.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] In such cases, the PSO variant is said to be local best (vs global best for the basic PSO).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] A commonly used swarm topology is the ring, in which each particle has just two neighbours, but there are many others.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] By using the ring topology, PSO can attain generation-level parallelism, significantly enhancing the evolutionary speed.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] There are several schools of thought as to why and how the PSO algorithm can perform optimization.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] As the system iterates and individuals learn from their neighbors, the distances in the search space between a particle and its neighbor tend to become smaller.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Thus the “p” and “g” terms in the formula become closer to one another, and the particle takes shorter steps through the search space as the swarm converges on optimal regions that have been discovered.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] If a new optimal region is found late in the search, the algorithm is able to return to its exploratory behavior, taking large steps again as particles adapt to the new discovery, and gradually converging or clustering around optimal regions.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] While the behavior of a single particle is easily conceptualized, a particle by itself has no optimization ability at all; the behavior of the swarm is more difficult to comprehend.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] A common belief amongst researchers is that the swarm behaviour varies between exploratory behaviour, that is, searching a broader region of the search-space, and exploitative behaviour, that is, a locally oriented search so as to get closer to a (possibly local) optimum.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This school of thought has been prevalent since the inception of PSO.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This school of thought contends that the PSO algorithm and its parameters must be chosen so as to properly balance between exploration and exploitation to avoid premature convergence to a local optimum yet still ensure a good rate of convergence to the optimum.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This belief is the precursor of many PSO variants, see below.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Another school of thought is that the behaviour of a PSO swarm is not well understood in terms of how it affects actual optimization performance, especially for higher-dimensional search-spaces and optimization problems that may be discontinuous, noisy, and time-varying.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This school of thought merely tries to find PSO algorithms and parameters that cause good performance regardless of how the swarm behaviour can be interpreted in relation to e.g. exploration and exploitation.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Such studies have led to the simplification of the PSO algorithm, see below.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Convergence of the sequence of solutions has been investigated for PSO.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] These analyses have resulted in guidelines for selecting PSO parameters that are believed to cause convergence to a point and prevent divergence of the swarm's particles (particles do not move unboundedly and will converge to somewhere).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] However, it was shown that these simplifications do not affect the boundaries found by these studies for parameter where the swarm is convergent.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Considerable effort has been made in recent years to weaken the modeling assumption utilized during the stability analysis of PSO, with the most recent generalized result applying to numerous PSO variants and utilized what was shown to be the minimal necessary modeling assumptions.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Convergence to a local optimum has been analyzed for PSO in and.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] It has been proven that PSO needs some modification to guarantee finding a local optimum.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This means that determining the convergence capabilities of different PSO algorithms and parameters still depends on empirical results.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] One attempt at addressing this issue is the development of an "orthogonal learning" strategy for an improved use of the information already existing in the relationship between **p** and **g**, so as to form a leading converging exemplar and to be effective with any PSO topology.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The aims are to improve the performance of PSO overall, including faster global convergence, higher solution quality, and stronger robustness.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] However, such studies do not provide theoretical evidence to actually prove their claims.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Without the need for a trade-off between convergence ('exploitation') and divergence ('exploration'), an adaptive mechanism can be introduced.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Adaptive particle swarm optimization (APSO) features better search efficiency than standard PSO.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] APSO can perform global search over the entire search space with a higher convergence speed.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] It enables automatic control of the inertia weight, acceleration coefficients, and other algorithmic parameters at the run time, thereby improving the search effectiveness and efficiency at the same time.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Also, APSO can act on the globally best particle to jump out of the likely local optima.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] However, APSO will introduce new algorithm parameters, it does not introduce additional design or implementation complexity nonetheless.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Besides, through the utilization of a scale-adaptive fitness evaluation mechanism, PSO can efficiently address computationally expensive optimization problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Numerous variants of even a basic PSO algorithm are possible.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] For example, there are different ways to initialize the particles and velocities (e.g. start with zero velocities instead), how to dampen the velocity, only update **p**i and **g** after the entire swarm has been updated, etc.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Some of these choices and their possible performance impact have been discussed in the literature.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] A series of standard implementations have been created by leading researchers, "intended for use both as a baseline for performance testing of improvements to the technique, as well as to represent PSO to the wider optimization community.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Having a well-known, strictly-defined standard algorithm provides a valuable point of comparison which can be used throughout the field of research to better test new advances." The latest is Standard PSO 2011 (SPSO-2011).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] In addition, some PSO variants have been developed to solve large-scale global optimization (LSGO) problems with more than 1000 dimensions.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Representative variants include competitive swarm optimizer (CSO) and level-based learning swarm optimizer (LLSO).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Recently, PSO has also been extended to solve multi-agent consensus-based distributed optimization problems, e.g., multi-agent consensus-based PSO with adaptive internal and external learning (MASOIE), etc.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] New and more sophisticated PSO variants are also continually being introduced in an attempt to improve optimization performance.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] There are certain trends in that research; one is to make a hybrid optimization method using PSO combined with other optimizers, e.g., combined PSO with biogeography-based optimization, and the incorporation of an effective learning method.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Another research trend is to try to alleviate premature convergence (that is, optimization stagnation), e.g. by reversing or perturbing the movement of the PSO particles, another approach to deal with premature convergence is the use of multiple swarms (multi-swarm optimization).
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The multi-swarm approach can also be used to implement multi-objective optimization.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Finally, there are developments in adapting the behavioural parameters of PSO during optimization.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Another school of thought is that PSO should be simplified as much as possible without impairing its performance; a general concept often referred to as Occam's razor.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Simplifying PSO was originally suggested by Kennedy and has been studied more extensively, where it appeared that optimization performance was improved, and the parameters were easier to tune and they performed more consistently across different optimization problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Another argument in favour of simplifying PSO is that metaheuristics can only have their efficacy demonstrated empirically by doing computational experiments on a finite number of optimization problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This means a metaheuristic such as PSO cannot be proven correct and this increases the risk of making errors in its description and implementation.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] This bias was because of a programming error, and has now been fixed.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Initialization of velocities may require extra inputs.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] The Bare Bones PSO variant has been proposed in 2003 by James Kennedy, and does not need to use velocity at all.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Another simpler variant is the accelerated particle swarm optimization (APSO), which also does not need to use velocity and can speed up the convergence in many applications.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] A simple demo code of APSO is available.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] In this variant of PSO one dispenses with both the particle's velocity and the particle's best position.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] where ${\vec {u}}$ is a random uniformly distributed vector, L is the typical length of the problem at hand, and $\beta \sim 0.1-0.7$ and $\alpha \sim 0.1-0.5$ are the parameters of the method.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] As a refinement of the method one can decrease $\alpha$ with each iteration, $\alpha _{n}=\alpha _{0}\gamma ^{n}$ , where n is the number of the iteration and $0<\gamma <1$ is the decrease control parameter.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] PSO has also been applied to multi-objective problems, in which the objective function comparison takes Pareto dominance into account when moving the PSO particles and non-dominated solutions are stored so as to approximate the pareto front.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] As the PSO equations given above work on real numbers, a commonly used method to solve discrete problems is to map the discrete search space to a continuous domain, to apply a classical PSO, and then to demap the result.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Such a mapping can be very simple (for example by just using rounded values) or more sophisticated.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] Usually a position and a velocity are represented by *n* real numbers, and these operators are simply -, *, +, and again +.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] But all these mathematical objects can be defined in a completely different way, in order to cope with binary problems (or more generally discrete ones), or even combinatorial ones.
[src:swarm-robotics/particle-swarm-optimization] One approach is to redefine the operators based on sets.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence systems consist typically of a population of simple agents or boids interacting locally with one another and with their environment.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The inspiration often comes from nature, especially biological systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The agents follow very simple rules, and although there is no centralized control structure dictating how individual agents should behave, local, and to a certain degree random, interactions between such agents lead to the emergence of "intelligent" global behavior, unknown to the individual agents.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Examples of swarm intelligence in natural systems include ant colonies, bee colonies, bird flocking, hawks hunting, animal herding, bacterial growth, fish schooling and microbial intelligence.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The application of swarm principles to robots is called *swarm robotics* while *swarm intelligence* refers to the more general set of algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] *Swarm prediction* has been used in the context of forecasting problems.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Similar approaches to those proposed for swarm robotics are considered for genetically modified organisms in synthetic collective intelligence.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Boids is an artificial life program, developed by Craig Reynolds in 1986, which simulates flocking.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It was published in 1987 in the proceedings of the ACM SIGGRAPH conference.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The name "boid" corresponds to a shortened version of "bird-oid object", which refers to a bird-like object.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] As with most artificial life simulations, Boids is an example of emergent behavior; that is, the complexity of Boids arises from the interaction of individual agents (the boids, in this case) adhering to a set of simple rules.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Self-propelled particles (SPP), also referred to as the *Vicsek model*, was introduced in 1995 by Vicsek *et al.* as a special case of the boids model introduced in 1986 by Reynolds.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] A swarm is modelled in SPP by a collection of particles that move with a constant speed but respond to a random perturbation by adopting at each time increment the average direction of motion of the other particles in their local neighbourhood.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] SPP models predict that swarming animals share certain properties at the group level, regardless of the type of animals in the swarm.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarming systems give rise to emergent behaviours which occur at many different scales, some of which are turning out to be both universal and robust.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It has become a challenge in theoretical physics to find minimal statistical models that capture these behaviours.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Social Potential Fields, developed in 1999 by John H.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Reif and Hongyan Wang , is one of the earliest models for Swarm Intelligence, developed for use for autonomous control of robot swarm systems that may consist of from hundreds to perhaps tens of thousands or more autonomous robots.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It is the first paper to apply a potential field model to distributed autonomous multi-robot control.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] A Social Potential Field defines simple artificial force laws between pairs of robots or robot groups.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] These force laws are inverse-power force laws, incorporating both attraction and repulsion, similar but more general compared to the force laws found in molecular dynamics.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] As one of simplest examples, they define a force law where attraction dominates over long distances and repulsion dominates on short distances.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The force laws can be distinct between various robots.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] An individual robot's motion is controlled by the resultant artificial force imposed by other robots and other components of the system.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields approach is distributed since the force calculations and motion control can be done in an asynchronous and distributed manner.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Using specially tailored force laws, they demonstrate complex behaviors and what might be viewed as "social relations' among robots.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Therefore, the model was termed "Social Potential Fields”.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] They demonstrated by computer simulations that the method can yield interesting and useful behaviors among robots, including clustering, guarding, escorting, patrolling, etc.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The 1999 paper envisioned many industrial and military applications such as assembling, transporting, hazardous inspection. patrolling, and military control of swarm systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Their simulations showed the social potential fields method is robust in that the method can tolerate errors in sensors and actuators.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The Social Potential Fields paper also extended the social potential fields model to use spring laws as force laws.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Evolutionary algorithms (EA), particle swarm optimization (PSO), differential evolution (DE), ant colony optimization (ACO) and their variants dominate the field of nature-inspired metaheuristics.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] This list includes algorithms published up to circa the year 2000.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] A large number of more recent metaphor-inspired metaheuristics have started to attract criticism in the research community for hiding their lack of novelty behind an elaborate metaphor.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] For algorithms published since that time, see List of metaphor-based metaheuristics.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Popular modern post-2000 examples include Grey Wolf Optimization (GWO), which replicates the dynamic hunting mechanisms and social leadership hierarchies of wolves in nature.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Metaheuristics lack a confidence in a solution.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] When appropriate parameters are determined, and when sufficient convergence stage is achieved, they often find a solution that is optimal, or near close to optimum – nevertheless, if one does not know optimal solution in advance, a quality of a solution is not known.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In spite of this obvious drawback it has been shown that these types of algorithms work well in practice, and have been extensively researched, and developed.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] One such instance is Ant-inspired Monte Carlo algorithm for Minimum Feedback Arc Set where this has been achieved probabilistically via hybridization of Monte Carlo algorithm with Ant Colony Optimization technique.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Ant colony optimization (ACO), introduced by Dorigo in his doctoral dissertation, is a class of optimization algorithms modeled on the actions of an ant colony.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] ACO is a probabilistic technique useful in problems that deal with finding better paths through graphs.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Artificial 'ants'—simulation agents—locate optimal solutions by moving through a parameter space representing all possible solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Natural ants lay down pheromones directing each other to resources while exploring their environment.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The simulated 'ants' similarly record their positions and the quality of their solutions, so that in later simulation iterations more ants locate for better solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Particle swarm optimization (PSO) is a global optimization algorithm for dealing with problems in which a best solution can be represented as a point or surface in an n-dimensional space.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Hypotheses are plotted in this space and seeded with an initial velocity, as well as a communication channel between the particles.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Particles then move through the solution space, and are evaluated according to some fitness criterion after each timestep.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Over time, particles are accelerated towards those particles within their communication grouping which have better fitness values.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The main advantage of such an approach over other global minimization strategies such as simulated annealing is that the large number of members that make up the particle swarm make the technique impressively resilient to the problem of local minima.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) is method of amplifying the collective intelligence of networked human groups using control algorithms modeled after natural swarms.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] ASI has also been used to enable groups of doctors to generate diagnoses with significantly higher accuracy than traditional methods.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] ASI has been used by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of the United Nations to help forecast famines in hotspots around the world.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarm Intelligence-based techniques can be used in a number of applications.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The U.S. military is investigating swarm techniques for controlling unmanned vehicles.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The European Space Agency is thinking about an orbital swarm for self-assembly and interferometry.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] NASA is investigating the use of swarm technology for planetary mapping.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Bekey discusses the possibility of using swarm intelligence to control nanobots within the body for the purpose of killing cancer tumors.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Conversely al-Rifaie and Aber have used stochastic diffusion search to help locate tumours.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence (SI) is increasingly applied in Internet of Things (IoT) systems, and by association to Intent-Based Networking (IBN), due to its ability to handle complex, distributed tasks through decentralized, self-organizing algorithms.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence has also been applied for data mining and cluster analysis.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Ant-based models are further subject of modern management theory.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarm intelligence can be used in many practical areas where multiple simple agents work together to solve complex problems efficiently.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It is commonly applied in optimization problems, such as route planning, scheduling, and resource allocation, where algorithms inspired by ants and birds help find the best solutions.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In robotics, swarm intelligence is used for coordinating multiple robots in tasks like search and rescue, warehouse automation, and environmental monitoring.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It is also widely used in network systems for efficient routing of data in the internet and wireless sensor networks.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In addition, swarm intelligence plays an important role in traffic and transportation systems, where it helps in traffic signal control, vehicle routing, and reducing congestion in smart cities.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In machine learning and data mining, it is used for feature selection, clustering, and improving model performance.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It is also applied in power systems for load balancing and energy optimization, especially in smart grids.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Furthermore, swarm intelligence is used in healthcare and bioinformatics for tasks like drug discovery and gene analysis, and in gaming and simulations to create realistic group behaviors such as crowd movement or flocking.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The use of swarm intelligence in telecommunication networks has also been researched, in the form of ant-based routing.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] This was pioneered separately by Dorigo et al. and Hewlett-Packard in the mid-1990s, with a number of variants existing.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Basically, this uses a probabilistic routing table rewarding/reinforcing the route successfully traversed by each "ant" (a small control packet) which flood the network.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] As the system behaves stochastically and is therefore lacking repeatability, there are large hurdles to commercial deployment.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Mobile media and new technologies have the potential to change the threshold for collective action due to swarm intelligence (Rheingold: 2002, P175).
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The location of transmission infrastructure for wireless communication networks is an important engineering problem involving competing objectives.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] A minimal selection of locations (or sites) are required subject to providing adequate area coverage for users.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] A very different, ant-inspired swarm intelligence algorithm, stochastic diffusion search (SDS), has been successfully used to provide a general model for this problem, related to circle packing and set covering.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] It has been shown that the SDS can be applied to identify suitable solutions even for large problem instances.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have also used ant-based routing in assigning aircraft arrivals to airport gates.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] At Southwest Airlines a software program uses swarm theory, or swarm intelligence—the idea that a colony of ants works better than one alone.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Each pilot acts like an ant searching for the best airport gate.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] "The pilot learns from his experience what's the best for him, and it turns out that that's the best solution for the airline," Douglas A.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] As a result, the "colony" of pilots always go to gates they can arrive at and depart from quickly.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The program can even alert a pilot of plane back-ups before they happen.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] "We can anticipate that it's going to happen, so we'll have a gate available," Lawson says.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Artists are using swarm technology as a means of creating complex interactive systems or simulating crowds.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Tim Burton's *Batman Returns* also made use of swarm technology for showing the movements of a group of bats.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Airlines have used swarm theory to simulate passengers boarding a plane.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Southwest Airlines researcher Douglas A.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Lawson used an ant-based computer simulation employing only six interaction rules to evaluate boarding times using various boarding methods.(Miller, 2010, xii-xviii).
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Networks of distributed users can be organized into "human swarms" through the implementation of real-time closed-loop control systems.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Developed by Louis Rosenberg in 2015, human swarming, also called artificial swarm intelligence, allows the collective intelligence of interconnected groups of people online to be harnessed.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The collective intelligence of the group often exceeds the abilities of any one member of the group.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In one such study, swarms of human radiologists connected together were tasked with diagnosing chest x-rays and demonstrated a 33% reduction in diagnostic errors as compared to the traditional human methods, and a 22% improvement over traditional machine-learning.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The University of California San Francisco (UCSF) School of Medicine released a preprint in 2021 about the diagnosis of MRI images by small groups of collaborating doctors.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The study showed a 23% increase in diagnostic accuracy when using Artificial Swarm Intelligence (ASI) technology compared to majority voting.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Swarm grammars are swarms of stochastic grammars that can be evolved to describe complex properties such as found in art and architecture.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] These grammars interact as agents behaving according to rules of swarm intelligence.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Such behavior can also suggest deep learning algorithms, in particular when mapping of such swarms to neural circuits is considered.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The "creativity" of this hybrid swarm system has been analysed under the philosophical light of the "rhizome" in the context of Deleuze's "Orchid and Wasp" metaphor.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] A more recent work of al-Rifaie et al., "Swarmic Sketches and Attention Mechanism", introduces a novel approach deploying the mechanism of 'attention' by adapting SDS to selectively attend to detailed areas of a digital canvas.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Once the attention of the swarm is drawn to a certain line within the canvas, the capability of PSO is used to produce a 'swarmic sketch' of the attended line.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The swarms move throughout the digital canvas in an attempt to satisfy their dynamic roles—attention to areas with more details—associated with them via their fitness function.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Having associated the rendering process with the concepts of attention, the performance of the participating swarms creates a unique, non-identical sketch each time the 'artist' swarms embark on interpreting the input line drawings.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In other works, while PSO is responsible for the sketching process, SDS controls the attention of the swarm.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] In a similar work, "Swarmic Paintings and Colour Attention", non-photorealistic images are produced using SDS algorithm which, in the context of this work, is responsible for colour attention.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] The "computational creativity" of the above-mentioned systems are discussed in through the two prerequisites of creativity (i.e. freedom and constraints) within the swarm intelligence's two infamous phases of exploration and exploitation.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-intelligence] Michael Theodore and Nikolaus Correll use swarm intelligent art installation to explore what it takes to have engineered systems to appear lifelike.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Relatively simple individual rules can produce a large set of complex swarm behaviors.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] A key component is the communication between the members of the group that build a system of constant feedback.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The swarm behavior involves constant change of individuals in cooperation with others, as well as the behavior of the whole group.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The design of swarm robotics systems is guided by swarm intelligence principles, which promote fault tolerance, scalability, and flexibility.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Unlike distributed robotic systems in general, swarm robotics emphasizes a large number of robots.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Miniaturization is also key factor in swarm robotics, as the effect of thousands of small robots can maximize the effect of the swarm-intelligent approach to achieve meaningful behavior at swarm-level through a greater number of interactions on an individual level.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Compared with individual robots, a swarm can commonly decompose its given missions to their subtasks; a swarm is more robust to partial failure and is more flexible with regard to different missions.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The phrase "swarm robotics" was reported to have first appeared in 1991, according to Google Scholar, but research regarding swarm robotics began to grow in the early 2000s.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The initial goal of studying swarm robotics was to test whether the concept of stigmergy could be used as a method for robots to indirectly communicate and coordinate with each other.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The result was demonstration of self-organized teams of robots that cooperate to solve a complex task, with the robots in the swarm taking different roles over time.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] This work was then expanded upon through the Swarmanoid project (2006–2010), which extended the ideas and algorithms developed in Swarm-bots to heterogeneous robot swarms composed of three types of robots—flying, climbing, and ground-based—that collaborated to carry out a search and retrieval task.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] There are many potential applications for swarm robotics.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] They include tasks that demand miniaturization (nanorobotics, microbotics), like distributed sensing tasks in micromachinery or the human body.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] A promising use of swarm robotics is in search and rescue missions.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Swarms of robots of different sizes could be sent to places that rescue-workers cannot reach safely, to explore the unknown environment and solve complex mazes via onboard sensors.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Swarm robotics can also be suited to tasks that demand cheap designs, for instance mining or agricultural shepherding tasks.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Drone swarms are used in target search, drone displays, and delivery.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] A drone display commonly uses multiple, lighted drones at night for an artistic display or advertising.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] A delivery drone swarm can carry multiple packages to a single destination at a time and overcome a single drone's payload and battery limitations.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] A drone swarm may undertake different flight formations to reduce overall energy consumption due to drag forces.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Drone swarming can also introduce additional control issues connected to human factors and the swarm operator.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Examples of this include high cognitive demand and complexity when interacting with multiple drones due to changing attention between different individual drones.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Communication between operator and swarm is also a central aspect.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] More controversially, swarms of military robots can form an autonomous army.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Naval forces have tested a swarm of autonomous boats that can steer and take offensive actions by themselves.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The boats are unmanned and can be fitted with any kind of kit to deter and destroy enemy vessels.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] During the Syrian Civil War, Russian forces in the region reported attacks on their main air force base in the country by swarms of fixed-wing drones loaded with explosives.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Another large set of applications may be solved using swarms of micro air vehicles, which are also broadly investigated nowadays.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Swarms of micro aerial vehicles have been already tested in tasks of autonomous surveillance, plume tracking, and reconnaissance in a compact phalanx.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Numerous works on cooperative swarms of unmanned ground and aerial vehicles have been conducted with target applications of cooperative environment monitoring, simultaneous localization and mapping, convoy protection, and moving target localization and tracking.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] In 2023, University of Washington and Microsoft researchers demonstrated acoustic swarms of tiny robots that create shape-changing smart speakers.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] These can be used for manipulating acoustic scenes to focus on or mute sounds from a specific region in a room.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Here, tiny robots cooperate with each other using sound signals, without any cameras, to navigate cooperatively with centimeter-level accuracy.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] These swarm devices spread out across a surface to create a distributed and reconfigurable wireless microphone array.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] They also navigate back to the charging station where they can be automatically recharged.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Most efforts have focused on relatively small groups of machines.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] However, a Kilobot swarm consisting of 1,024 individual robots was demonstrated by Harvard in 2014, the largest to date.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Another example of miniaturization is the LIBOT Robotic System that involves a low cost robot built for outdoor swarm robotics.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] The robots are also made with provisions for indoor use via Wi-Fi, since the GPS sensors provide poor communication inside buildings.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Another such attempt is the micro robot (Colias), built in the Computer Intelligence Lab at the University of Lincoln, UK.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] This micro robot is built on a 4 cm circular chassis and is a low-cost and open platform for use in a variety of swarm robotics applications.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Additionally, progress has been made in the application of autonomous swarms in the field of manufacturing, known as swarm 3D printing.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] This is particularly useful for the production of large structures and components, where traditional 3D printing is not able to be utilized due to hardware size constraints.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] Miniaturization and mass mobilization allows the manufacturing system to achieve scale invariance, not limited in effective build volume.
[src:swarm-robotics/swarm-robotics] While in its early stage of development, swarm 3D printing is currently being commercialized by startup companies.
